[H[2J[3J[1m[34m┄[0m[1m[34musing gepa to hone claude haiku on github bug fixes (+20% solve on untrained bugs)[0m

[3m2026-04-19[0m

Claude haiku 4.5 solves 65% of real github bugs with a 14-word seed prompt. I ran GEPA (a prompt-evolution library out of dspy) against
it for 7 hours on 20 bug-fix challenges, and the optimized prompt takes the same model to 85% on 9 unseen bugs it never trained on. 20
points of solve rate from prose alone — nothing else about the setup changed.

The system isn't novel. It's three off-the-shelf pieces glued together. ]8;;https://github.com/gepa-ai/gepa\[34mGEPA[0m]8;;\ is the prompt optimizer (pareto-style mutation + selection
out of the dspy project). ]8;;https://github.com/twaldin/harness\[34mharness[0m]8;;\ is my python lib that wraps 6 AI coding CLIs — claude code, codex, opencode, gemini, cursor, aider —
behind one API so GEPA can drive any of them as the executor. ]8;;https://github.com/twaldin/agentelo\[34magentelo[0m]8;;\ is my leaderboard / challenge runner; it scores each challenge as
[33mtests_fixed / tests_broken_before[0m and reports the mean. Hone is the ~300-line coordinator wiring them together: GEPA proposes a system
prompt variant, harness runs the executor CLI with that prompt, agentelo grades the resulting diff against the real PR's test suite.

(The mutator here was sonnet via the claude code CLI on my max sub, so no API billing — but the point of hone is that any CLI can drive
any other CLI, not that it happened to be free this run.)

[1m[34m┄┄[0m[1m[34mtraining trajectory[0m

20 training challenges pulled from 5 repos —[33m click[0m (9),[33m marshmallow[0m (5),[33m qs[0m (4),[33m jinja[0m (2),[33m koa[0m (1) — all real PRs from the last 90 days
with clean red/green test suites.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
[1m iter [0m[1m candidate                  [0m[1m full valset (20) [0m[1m delta vs seed [0m
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
 0     seed (14 words)             0.5476            —             
 1     candidate 1 (6-step v1)     0.8583            +0.3107       
 2     candidate 2 (6-step v2)     0.9176            +0.3700       
 3     candidate 3 (tied on full)  0.9176            +0.3700       
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Seed solves 11/20. Candidate 2 solves 18/20. Third candidate climbed on GEPA's subsample eval but tied on the full valset, so GEPA
stopped. Budget was 20 iters; actual spend was 4.

[1m[34m┄┄[0m[1m[34mholdout — 9 unseen bugs × 3 samples[0m

Holdout has zero overlap with training:[33m marshmallow-pr2892, marshmallow-pr2894, marshmallow-pr2901, click-pr3152, requests-pr7205,[0m
[33mqs-pr350, qs-pr506, qs-pr335, flask-pr5917[0m.[33m requests[0m and[33m flask[0m weren't in training at all. Three independent samples per prompt = 27
runs per column.

─────────────────────────────────
[1m sample [0m[1m seed   [0m[1m honed  [0m[1m delta   [0m
─────────────────────────────────
 1       0.6496  0.8889  +0.2393 
 2       0.7607  0.8718  +0.1111 
 3       0.5385  0.7778  +0.2393 
 mean    0.6496  0.8462  +0.1966 
─────────────────────────────────

All three samples improved. No regressions. Training lift was +0.37, holdout lift is +0.20 — about half transfers, which is roughly the
train/test gap you'd expect from any ML setup.

[1m[34m┄┄[0m[1m[34mwhat GEPA actually discovered[0m

The diff between candidate 1 and candidate 2 is small, but every change points at the same failure mode: haiku fixes the first visible
failing test and declares victory.

───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
[1m area         [0m[1m 1 → 2                                                                                       [0m
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
 test reading  "read the failing tests" → "read ALL the failing tests" + "note every failing test case".   
 root cause    "trace the failure" → "trace each failure". Added multi-failure root-cause check.           
 fix           Added: "if the same logical error appears in multiple places, fix all of them".             
 edge cases    Added concrete examples (encoding, array notation, option flags) + a config-check clause.   
 verification  "confirm all tests pass" → "keep iterating until every originally-failing test passes".     
 persistence   "persist" → "persist through partial fixes. partial progress is not success."               
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The honed prompt isn't clever. It's "don't trust the first green, check every test, keep looking for a second bug site". GEPA spent its
three accepted mutations localizing exactly that one failure mode — and because that failure mode generalizes across codebases, the fix
generalizes too.

Seed (0.5476):

[32m────────────────────[0m
[33mYou are an AI coding agent fixing a bug in an open-source project.
[0m[33mApproach each task carefully and produce a minimal, correct fix.
[0m[32m────────────────────[0m

Candidate 2, the one that shipped (train 0.9176 / holdout 0.8462):

[32m────────────────────[0m
[33mYou are an AI coding agent fixing a bug in an open-source project.
[0m[33m
[0m[33mFollow this process for every task:
[0m[33m
[0m[33m1. Read ALL the failing tests first. Before touching any source code, read the
[0m[33m   relevant test files completely. Run the test suite and capture the full
[0m[33m   output — note every failing test case, not just the first one. Group the
[0m[33m   failures by type to understand the full scope of what needs to be fixed.
[0m[33m
[0m[33m2. Find the root cause. Trace each failure to the specific line(s) responsible.
[0m[33m   Read the source code — not just the test file. If multiple test cases fail,
[0m[33m   check whether they share a single root cause or require separate fixes.
[0m[33m   Check git log or comments if the logic is unclear.
[0m[33m
[0m[33m3. Fix the root cause, not the symptom. Make the minimal change that makes the
[0m[33m   failing tests pass without breaking existing tests. Do not add workarounds
[0m[33m   or special-case patches if the underlying logic is wrong. If the same
[0m[33m   logical error appears in multiple places in the source, fix all of them.
[0m[33m
[0m[33m4. Handle edge cases. If the tests involve edge cases (empty strings,
[0m[33m   null/undefined, special characters, numeric boundaries, nested structures,
[0m[33m   encoding, array notation, option flags), make sure your fix handles all of
[0m[33m   them — not just the obvious case. For libraries with configurable behavior,
[0m[33m   check whether option or configuration values affect the code path you are
[0m[33m   fixing.
[0m[33m
[0m[33m5. Verify all tests pass. After editing, run the full test suite. If some
[0m[33m   previously failing tests still fail, do not stop — re-read those specific
[0m[33m   failing test cases, understand precisely what they expect, and revise your
[0m[33m   fix. Keep iterating until every originally-failing test passes and no
[0m[33m   regressions are introduced.
[0m[33m
[0m[33m6. Persist through partial fixes. If your fix makes some but not all tests
[0m[33m   pass, treat that as an incomplete fix. Re-read the remaining failures
[0m[33m   carefully, check if there is a second location in the source that needs the
[0m[33m   same or a related fix, and continue. Partial progress is not success.
[0m[33m
[0m[33mKeep changes minimal and correct. Do not refactor unrelated code or add new
[0m[33mtests unless explicitly required.
[0m[32m────────────────────[0m

[1m[34m┄┄[0m[1m[34mwhy haiku and not anything else[0m

Haiku sits in the goldilocks band for this kind of prompt honing. Too weak, and the executor can't actually follow the methodology the
mutator writes — adding "check for a second bug site" to the prompt doesn't help if the model couldn't trace to the first bug site
reliably. Too strong, and the bare seed prompt already matches what the model does internally, so there's nothing for GEPA to discover.

I ran overnight seed baselines on four neighbours to find the next goldilocks target. The news was mostly flat:

• [33mopencode + gemini-2.5-flash[0m — seed in the 0.2 range. Followed up a short hone run; no meaningful lift. Executor is too weak to
  actually execute the 6-step methodology.
• [33mcodex + gpt-5.2[0m — saturated at seed (already in the 0.85+ band). GEPA mutations produced no measurable improvement over the
  already-strong baseline.
• [33mcodex + gpt-5.4-mini[0m — saturated at seed.
• [33mcodex + gpt-5.4-mini-fast[0m — saturated at seed.

The earlier gpt-5.4 run sat in the same bucket — bare "minimal correct fix" already matches gpt-5.4's internal behavior, zero movement
from GEPA. So the window where prompt honing moves the number is narrower than I'd hoped: somewhere in the 0.5–0.7 seed band. Outside
that, either the executor can't use the better prompt (floor) or doesn't need it (ceiling).

[1m[34m┄┄[0m[1m[34mthe 3-challenge run I wasted two days on[0m

First attempt trained on only 3 challenges ([33mqs-pr335, click-pr2846, marshmallow-pr2901[0m). Training score hit 1.0 but the A/B on 6 unseen
bugs regressed from 0.9167 seed to 0.8102 honed. GEPA had memorized qs-pr335's query-string specifics and tanked on unrelated bugs.
Scaling training to 20 challenges across 5 repos was the fix — probably obvious in hindsight (diversity of training distribution matters
for generalization) but I only caught it after the holdout came back worse.

